erpetrators and How They Dealt with Their Parents’ Actions -- tPART FIVE Personal Reflections -- t12 Always Moving Forward -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe testimonies of individuals who survived the Holocaust as children pose distinct emotional and intellectual challenges for researchers: as now-adult interviewees recall profound childhood experiences of suffering and persecution, they also invoke their own historical awareness and memories of their postwar lives, requiring readers to follow simultaneous, disparate narratives. This interdisciplinary volume brings together historians, psychologists, and other scholars to explore child survivors’ accounts. With a central focus on the Kestenberg Holocaust Child Survivor Archive’s over 1,500 testimonies, it not only enlarges our understanding of the Holocaust empirically but illuminates the methodological, theoretical, and institutional dimensions of this unique form of historical record.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aJewish children in the HolocaustvInterviews. 0aJewish children in the HolocaustxInterviews. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xChildrenvInterviews. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xInterviewsxChildren. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh1 aBass-Wichelhaus, Helene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrüning, Christina Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Beth B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Sharon Kangisser, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Sharon Kangisser, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEinert, Katrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFogelman, E